&gt; &gt; &gt; Hi everybody,
&gt; &gt; &gt; I&#39;ve written a TestCase for one class.
&gt; &gt; &gt; Is there a way to test another class with this test?
&gt; &gt; &gt; The problem is: it is impossible to pass second one as parameter 
to &quot;Test
&gt; &gt; &gt; suite()&quot; method (as it is static and passing will give one result:
&gt; &gt; &gt; last class will be tested twice). Changing test is not really good
&gt; &gt; &gt; (as there will be some more classes that I would like to test with
&gt; &gt; &gt; TestCase).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I assume you want to run many tests at one time. The normal way is to
&gt; &gt; create a class that collects the TestCase  classes together:
&gt; [...]
&gt; 
&gt; No. There idea is:
&gt; public interface IF{
&gt;   public static Object calculate(String str,int i);
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; public class A implements IF{
&gt;   //implementation
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; public class B implements IF{
&gt;   //implementation
&gt; }
&gt; //Strategy pattern is used
&gt; 
&gt; I know that result will be the same running class A and B. I&#39;ve made 
&gt; test for class A, eg TestA, now I want to test B with this test. The 
&gt; problem is: to pass class B to that test and test A and B at one time.

OK. So you want the same tests for each implementation, but you want to write 
them once. You want the &quot;Abstract Test Case&quot; pattern. Start here:

http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?AbstractTestCases

The basic pattern is this: 

abstract class IFTest extends TestCase {
    test1() {
        IF theIf = createIF();
        // Call methods
        // Make assertions
    }
    ...
    abstract IF createIF();
}

class ATest extends IFTest {
    IF createIF() {
         return new A();
    }
}

class BTest extends IFTest {
    IF createIF() {
         return new B();
    }
}

Now run tests ATest and BTest in your test suite. Each inherits its test 
methods from IFTest, so they run the same tests. ATest tests with A objects 
and BTest tests with B objects. Do *not* add IFTest to your test suite.

